    longDescription: 'Mortal Kombat\'s "Mortal Monday" simultaneous console release on September 13, 1993 was the most anticipated home conversion of the era. The game had spent the year generating congressional hearings, editorial coverage, and parental concern; its digitised violence and "fatality" finishing moves had made it the most controversial game in history. Nintendo\'s SNES content guidelines prohibited blood and excessive violence; Sega had no equivalent policy. The result was two versions of the same game with fundamentally different content, sold at the same price on the same day to the same demographic.\n\nThe SNES version replaced blood with grey "sweat," altered fatalities to remove decapitation and dismemberment, and converted some finishing move elements to remove graphic content. The Genesis version included the blood code ABACABB — which spelled out the name of a Genesis album — entered at the options screen, which restored the game to arcade accuracy. Sega\'s marketing made the code\'s existence explicit: advertisements promoted the Genesis version as the one "with the blood."\n\nThe commercial result was decisive. The Genesis version outsold the SNES version by a ratio variously estimated at 2:1 to 3:1. The content difference had become a purchasing criterion in a way that no previous game had tested. The controversy contributed directly to the formation of the Entertainment Software Rating Board in September 1994, one year after Mortal Monday, establishing the rating framework that still governs North American game publishing.',
